Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.550 --> 00:00:07.020
Good evening.

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:09.940
My name is Francis Ma,
and I'm a Product Manager

00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:12.930
in the Developers product group.

00:00:12.930 --> 00:00:17.900
There are many ingredients
in building a successful app.

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:21.800
And one of these is
having a great design.

00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:26.310
Deign shapes your users'
experiences and motions

00:00:26.310 --> 00:00:28.270
when using your app.

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:33.530
And having great design not only
helps them utilize and navigate

00:00:33.530 --> 00:00:38.370
through your app, but
it also delights them,

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:41.990
and provides a great experience
across different platforms

00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:43.274
and form factors.

00:00:43.274 --> 00:00:44.690
Now, these were
some of the things

00:00:44.690 --> 00:00:48.650
that we want as well from
our own apps from Google.

00:00:48.650 --> 00:00:52.940
And so we've created
Material Design.

00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:54.820
Material Design
is a design system

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:58.460
that governs interaction,
visual, and motion design

00:00:58.460 --> 00:00:59.460
principles.

00:00:59.460 --> 00:01:02.620
And that means it guides
how your app should look,

00:01:02.620 --> 00:01:07.340
feel, move, and adapt
across different platforms,

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:11.160
providing a
consistent experience.

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:15.040
There are four principles to
building a Material Design app.

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:17.990
First is about
tangible services,

00:01:17.990 --> 00:01:20.130
where your interaction
cues are based

00:01:20.130 --> 00:01:24.470
on how physical objects
work in the real world.

00:01:24.470 --> 00:01:28.230
Second is about
print like design,

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:32.650
where your content and
colors are bold, graphic,

00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:34.110
and intentional.

00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:38.770
[INAUDIBLE] refined to fit the
look and feel of your brand.

00:01:38.770 --> 00:01:41.930
Third is about using
meaningful motion

00:01:41.930 --> 00:01:44.220
to draw the user's
attention, and provide

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:47.080
a sense of continuity as
they move from one screen

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:49.080
to the next.

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:52.420
And fourth is about
an adaptive design

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:54.760
that can scale and
have a consistent look

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:57.340
and feel across
different form factors,

00:01:57.340 --> 00:02:00.240
whether you're building
for a phone, a tablet,

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:01.630
or even for a TV.

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:03.500
And for your users,
that also means

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.710
that they don't have to
relearn your app as they

00:02:05.710 --> 00:02:06.585
switch from devices.

00:02:09.110 --> 00:02:10.600
And through these
four principles,

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:12.960
Material Design helps
you express your brand

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:15.980
through the use of these
bold and graphic colors.

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:19.120
It also helps you
delight your users

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:22.590
with motion and a
sense of consistency

00:02:22.590 --> 00:02:24.450
across different platforms.

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:28.310
And most importantly, it helps
you increase user engagement

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.820
and drive growth, as we've
seen from many examples of apps

00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:35.880
who've switched to
using Material Design.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:40.280
Here is a before and
after of Snapdeal

00:02:40.280 --> 00:02:44.110
after going through
Material Design.

00:02:44.110 --> 00:02:45.610
And there are many
great examples

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:47.318
we've seen from
different developers that

00:02:47.318 --> 00:02:50.480
have seen great success
by going Material Design.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:55.580
For example, Trello is an app
that lets you organize things

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:57.240
by creating boards.

00:02:57.240 --> 00:02:58.740
And by going Material
Design they've

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:01.280
seen an increase in user
interaction and engagement.

00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:06.685
Another example is Pocket
Cast, a great podcast

00:03:06.685 --> 00:03:09.260
app that has seen
an increase in sales

00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:11.680
after going Material Design.

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:13.780
And those are just
some of the examples,

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:15.790
and we have many
more that we have

00:03:15.790 --> 00:03:18.380
seen since the past
year and a half

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:20.180
introducing Material Design.

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:21.710
There are over
hundreds of thousands

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:24.270
of apps that have
updated their design.

00:03:24.270 --> 00:03:26.370
And you can see some
of these great examples

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:33.060
at g.co/MaterialShowcase.

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:35.540
And in addition, we've
been working hard

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:39.340
to help you implement
Material Design with resources

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:41.971
available on design.google.com.

00:03:41.971 --> 00:03:47.600
From there you'll find things
like the latest design specs.

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:51.210
An icon assets library that
you can just take and put them

00:03:51.210 --> 00:03:52.850
in your app.

00:03:52.850 --> 00:03:55.590
Also a devices tool that
provides the latest device

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.960
specs and metrics for things
like screen densities and sizes

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:01.259
for the most popular devices.

00:04:01.259 --> 00:04:03.550
And for those of you who are
into interactive learning,

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:06.990
we have a Udacity course
on Material Design as well.

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:09.570
And of course, for all the
developers in the room,

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:12.650
most importantly is
implementing this in code.

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:15.220
And that's where we have
the Android Support Library,

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.779
with reusable UI components
that you can just drop in.

00:04:18.779 --> 00:04:21.430
And with using the
support library,

00:04:21.430 --> 00:04:23.960
it also means that
your app will work

00:04:23.960 --> 00:04:28.210
on older versions of Android.

00:04:28.210 --> 00:04:30.393
So be sure to check
out design.google.com

00:04:30.393 --> 00:04:32.710
and learn more about
Material Design.

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:37.520
So going beyond
design, I also want

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:39.940
to share with you some of
the tools and services that

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:43.680
can help you develop your app,
grow and engage an audience,

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:45.400
and earn more money.

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:46.760
Let's start with develop.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:50.320
These are tools and services to
help you build your app easier,

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:54.570
faster, and better.

00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:56.150
Android Studio.

00:04:56.150 --> 00:04:59.560
We've introduced Android Studio
2.0 just a few weeks ago.

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:02.300
And this is a massive
update from the version 1.0

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:04.580
that we made a year ago.

00:05:04.580 --> 00:05:07.400
Specifically, we worked
really hard to improve

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:10.750
the speed and productivity
of using Android Studio.

00:05:10.750 --> 00:05:13.500
We've taken your
feedback on this.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:16.510
One of the notable
features is Instant Run.

00:05:16.510 --> 00:05:19.850
Instant Run lets you
take code and deploy that

00:05:19.850 --> 00:05:23.000
into a running app, whether
it's a connected physical device

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:24.400
on an emulator.

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:28.110
Here is an example of what
Instant Run looks like.

00:05:28.110 --> 00:05:32.780
As you make changes, you
can see that reflected

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:36.950
in your running app
in just seconds.

00:05:36.950 --> 00:05:40.740
So this is a great way to
really refine and iterate

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:46.580
your design UI, and to do that
in a very productive manner.

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:50.060
In addition to
having Instant Run

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:52.010
we've also worked hard
to improve the end

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:54.580
to end full build
and deploy cycle.

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:56.610
It used to take a minute.

00:05:56.610 --> 00:05:58.635
Now it takes only 20 seconds.

00:06:01.550 --> 00:06:03.730
And other great features
that we've been working on

00:06:03.730 --> 00:06:06.280
is revamping our emulator.

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:09.070
Again, we've heard your
feedback on the emulator,

00:06:09.070 --> 00:06:11.990
and we've been working hard
to make this much faster

00:06:11.990 --> 00:06:13.220
than before.

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:15.790
With this new emulator,
it now runs faster

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:18.560
than most physical
Android devices.

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:21.670
And we've also improved
the UI to make it easier

00:06:21.670 --> 00:06:28.960
for you to emulate things
like device locations,

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.550
or to do things like
device orientation,

00:06:31.550 --> 00:06:33.350
and even emulating phone calls.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:41.770
Another great addition
to Android Studio 2.0

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:43.082
is a new GPU profiler.

00:06:43.082 --> 00:06:45.040
Now, for those of you
who are building graphics

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:48.480
intensive apps, like games,
performance is critical.

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:51.340
And oftentimes, debugging
your graphics code

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:53.110
is very time consuming.

00:06:53.110 --> 00:06:55.910
And so with this new GPU
profiler and debugger,

00:06:55.910 --> 00:06:58.270
it records your
entire GPU stream,

00:06:58.270 --> 00:07:00.370
and lets you play
that back, saving you

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:02.510
countless hours of debugging.

00:07:02.510 --> 00:07:05.530
It's a great thing to check out.

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:09.260
And since Android Studio was
built on top of IntelliJ,

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:11.470
their advancements
and enhancements

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:13.480
propels us even faster.

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:15.510
And with the latest
version of Android Studio,

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:17.780
we've updated to
the IntelliJ 15,

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:20.492
which was just released
several weeks ago as well.

00:07:20.492 --> 00:07:22.450
And through this update
you'll see improvements

00:07:22.450 --> 00:07:25.690
on usability and testing.

00:07:25.690 --> 00:07:28.250
So there are lots of great
features with Android Studio

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:29.620
2.0 updates.

00:07:29.620 --> 00:07:33.660
And for those rare developers
in this room who may be still

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:36.600
on our old deprecated
Eclipse tool,

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:40.520
now is a really good time
to check out Android Studio.

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:46.020
This is all available through
our Canary channel today.

00:07:46.020 --> 00:07:48.120
In addition to
providing tools, we also

00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:51.990
have cloud services to help
you build your app easier.

00:07:51.990 --> 00:07:55.330
Firebase is a mobile
back-end as a service that

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:57.610
provides a real
time database that

00:07:57.610 --> 00:08:00.550
lets you easily store
data, and also synchronizes

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:03.110
across devices in real time.

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:07.572
Also, it includes offline
handling automatically.

00:08:07.572 --> 00:08:09.030
Another great
feature with Firebase

00:08:09.030 --> 00:08:12.610
is user authentication, which
lets you integrate things

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:16.410
like Google sign-in, Facebook
login, or your own custom email

00:08:16.410 --> 00:08:18.340
and password login,
so that you don't

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:21.040
have to reinvent the wheel
of creating your own user

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:23.550
authentication.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:26.520
Another great feature is static
hosting, which is CDN backed

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:29.360
and SSL enabled static
hosting that lets you quickly

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:33.100
spin up a mobile web page, or
even surf your image assets.

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:36.320
Through Firebase Google
provides us infrastructure

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:39.460
so that you don't have to worry
about that, or the scaling,

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:41.299
and you can really
focus on building

00:08:41.299 --> 00:08:45.480
differentiated
features for your app.

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.110
In addition to helping you
build easier and faster,

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:51.920
we also have tools to
help you build better.

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:55.170
And this is where Cloud
Test Lab comes in.

00:08:55.170 --> 00:09:04.160
We know that over 44% of
bugs are discovered by users

00:09:04.160 --> 00:09:09.000
after an app is launched,
and that 84% of users

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.430
would just abandon the
app after experiencing

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:13.450
an error for the second time.

00:09:13.450 --> 00:09:16.770
So ensuring your app is of high
quality before it is released

00:09:16.770 --> 00:09:18.940
is very important.

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:23.570
And with Cloud Test Lab, we help
you run automated and custom

00:09:23.570 --> 00:09:27.080
tests through virtual
or physical devices

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:30.150
that are hosted in the
Google data centers.

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:34.230
We provide access to the
most popular Android devices,

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.970
and also let you run
these tests in parallel.

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:40.190
So you can test things in
different languages, device

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:43.120
orientations, or even in
different Android versions,

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:44.550
all in parallel.

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:45.940
And doing this is very easy.

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.210
All you have to do
is upload your APK.

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:51.470
And with our robo
tests that means,

00:09:51.470 --> 00:09:54.110
even if you have not
written any test case,

00:09:54.110 --> 00:09:56.220
we automatically
crawl through the app

00:09:56.220 --> 00:10:00.250
and capture screenshots,
videos, and crash logs for you.

00:10:00.250 --> 00:10:02.030
And we also worked
hard to integrate this

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:05.480
into your product-- into
your development workflow,

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:09.100
and made it accessible through
Google Play in Android Studio.

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:11.290
So when you publish an app
through the alpha or beta

00:10:11.290 --> 00:10:14.450
channel of Google Play, we
will automatically run your APK

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:16.070
through the Cloud
Test Lab to help

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:18.200
you catch those errors
early, before it

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:21.090
gets broadly distributed.

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:24.290
This feature is now in beta,
and we're continuing our roll

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:25.400
out in the coming months.

00:10:28.170 --> 00:10:31.079
So I've talked about some tools
that help you develop your app.

